Q: The four adjacent digits in the 1000-digit number that have the greatest product are 9 × 9 × 8 × 9 = 5832.
//Take from Website
Find the thirteen adjacent digits in the 1000-digit number that have the greatest product. What is the value of this product?

Ans: We take number as a string, split it so we get an array of 1000 elements, We then loop till 987 i.e., (1000-13). Each time we'll take first 13 chars of the num string and add it in another array num2 and then multiple all the elements in this array and add to variable "lar" if it's highest. Then in each while loop, we'll remove the 1st element of the "num" string so that we can work on other 999, 998, 997 chars etc.

=end

num = ""
num1 = num.split('')
n = 1
lar = 1
while n < 988 do
    num2 = num1.first 13
    mul = 1
    num2.each do |num|
        numToInt = num.to_i
        mul = mul * numToInt
    end
    lar = mul if mul > lar
    num1 = num1.drop(1)
    n = n + 1
end
puts lar